Here's an iRule for HTTP to HTTPS redirect:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    HTTP::redirect "https://[HTTP::host][HTTP::uri]"
}

This triggers on every HTTP request and redirects the client to the same host and URI but using HTTPS protocol.

Implement rate limiting using tables in an iRule:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    set client_ip [IP::client_addr]
    set rate [table incr -subtable rate_limit $client_ip]
    table timeout -subtable rate_limit $client_ip 60
    if { $rate > 100 } {
        HTTP::respond 429 content "Rate limit exceeded"
    }
}

This limits each client IP to 100 requests per 60-second window.

Use a switch statement in your iRule:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    switch -glob [HTTP::uri] {
        "/api/*" { pool api_pool }
        "/images/*" { pool static_pool }
        "/admin/*" { pool admin_pool }
        default { pool default_pool }
    }
}

This routes traffic to different pools based on the URI path.

Common headers to insert via iRules or HTTP profile: 1) X-Forwarded-For: [IP::client_addr] - Original client IP, 2) X-Forwarded-Proto: https/http - Original protocol, 3) X-Forwarded-Port: [TCP::client_port] - Original client port. Example iRule:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    HTTP::header insert "X-Forwarded-For" [IP::client_addr]
    HTTP::header insert "X-Forwarded-Proto" "https"
}

Data groups store lists for efficient lookups. Create and use them as follows:

1) Create address data group:
tmsh create ltm data-group internal blocked_ips type ip records add { 10.0.0.1 { } 10.0.0.2 { } }

2) Use in iRule:
when CLIENT_ACCEPTED {
    if { [class match [IP::client_addr] equals blocked_ips] } {
        reject
    }
}

Supported types: string, address (IP), and integer.

Implement cookie-based persistence:

when HTTP_RESPONSE {
    HTTP::cookie insert name "SERVERID" value [IP::server_addr]
}

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { [HTTP::cookie exists "SERVERID"] } {
        set server [HTTP::cookie "SERVERID"]
        pool my_pool member $server 80
    }
}

This inserts a cookie with the server IP and uses it for subsequent request routing.

Use HTTP::respond to send responses directly from an iRule:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { [active_members my_pool] == 0 } {
        HTTP::respond 503 content "<html><body><h1>Service Unavailable</h1></body></html>" "Content-Type" "text/html"
    }
}

Syntax: HTTP::respond <status_code> content "<body>" "Header-Name" "Header-Value"

'members add' appends new members to an existing pool while keeping current members. 'members replace-all-with' completely replaces all pool members with the specified list. Examples:

# Add members
tmsh modify ltm pool my_pool members add { 10.0.0.3:80 }

# Replace all members
tmsh modify ltm pool my_pool members replace-all-with { 10.0.0.1:80 10.0.0.2:80 }

Use add for expansion, replace-all-with for complete reconfiguration.

Serve a maintenance page when all pool members are down:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { [active_members [LB::server pool]] == 0 } {
        HTTP::respond 503 content {
<html>
<head><title>Maintenance</title></head>
<body>
<h1>We'll be right back</h1>
<p>The system is undergoing maintenance.</p>
</body>
</html>
        } "Content-Type" "text/html"
    }
}

This checks active members before each request.

To access HTTP request body:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { [HTTP::header "Content-Length"] ne "" && [HTTP::header "Content-Length"] > 0 } {
        HTTP::collect [HTTP::header "Content-Length"]
    }
}

when HTTP_REQUEST_DATA {
    set payload [HTTP::payload]
    log local0. "Request body: $payload"
    # Process or modify payload
}

HTTP::collect triggers HTTP_REQUEST_DATA event when body is available.

Modify response content using HTTP_RESPONSE_DATA event:

when HTTP_RESPONSE {
    if { [HTTP::header "Content-Type"] contains "text/html" } {
        HTTP::collect [HTTP::header "Content-Length"]
    }
}

when HTTP_RESPONSE_DATA {
    set payload [HTTP::payload]
    set payload [string map {"old.domain.com" "new.domain.com"} $payload]
    HTTP::payload replace 0 [HTTP::payload length] $payload
}

This replaces domain references in HTML responses.

Configure modern cipher suites in Client SSL profile:

tmsh modify ltm profile client-ssl my_ssl ciphers 'TLSv1.2+TLSv1.3:!aNULL:!eNULL:!EXPORT:!DES:!RC4:!3DES:!MD5:!PSK' options { dont-insert-empty-fragments no-tlsv1 no-tlsv1.1 no-sslv3 }

The 'options' setting disables older protocol versions. Prefer ECDHE cipher suites for Perfect Forward Secrecy.

The LB_SELECTED event triggers after BIG-IP's load balancing algorithm has selected a pool member but before the connection is established. Use it to: 1) Log the selected server, 2) Override the selection, 3) Add headers based on selected server. Example:

when LB_SELECTED {
    log local0. "Selected: [LB::server addr]:[LB::server port]"
    # Override selection if needed
    # LB::reselect pool other_pool
}

Enable HTTP compression to reduce bandwidth:

1) Create or use compression profile:
tmsh create ltm profile http-compression my_compress defaults-from httpcompression content-type-include { text/ application/json application/javascript }

2) Assign to virtual server:
tmsh modify ltm virtual my_vs profiles add { my_compress }

Compression reduces response size for text-based content, improving performance for clients. Monitor CPU impact on high-traffic systems.

HTTP::collect buffers incoming HTTP data for inspection. It's used before HTTP_REQUEST_DATA or HTTP_RESPONSE_DATA events to collect the payload:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    # Collect up to 1MB of request body
    HTTP::collect 1048576
}

when HTTP_REQUEST_DATA {
    # Now HTTP::payload is available
    set body [HTTP::payload]
}

Use it for content inspection, modification, or validation.

FQDN (Fully Qualified Domain Name) pool members resolve DNS names dynamically:

tmsh create ltm node web.example.com fqdn { name web.example.com }
tmsh create ltm pool my_pool members add { web.example.com:80 }

Configure DNS resolution:
tmsh modify sys dns name-servers add { 8.8.8.8 }

FQDN nodes automatically update when DNS records change, useful for cloud environments.

RULE_INIT triggers once when an iRule is loaded or BIG-IP starts. Use it to initialize static variables or configurations:

when RULE_INIT {
    # Set static configuration values
    set static::max_requests 1000
    set static::timeout 300
    set static::debug 0
}

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { $rate > $static::max_requests } {
        HTTP::respond 429
    }
}

static:: variables persist across events and connections.

iRule priority determines execution order when multiple iRules are assigned to a virtual server. Lower numbers execute first (default is 500). Set priority:

tmsh modify ltm virtual my_vs rules { first_rule { priority 100 } second_rule { priority 200 } }

Use priorities to ensure: security rules run first, modifications happen in correct order, logging runs last. iRules in the same event run sequentially by priority.

'when' defines event handlers - it specifies what events trigger your code (e.g., when HTTP_REQUEST, when CLIENT_ACCEPTED). 'if' is a conditional statement within an event handler that controls code flow based on conditions.

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    # This code runs on every HTTP request
    if { [HTTP::uri] starts_with "/admin" } {
        # This runs only if URI starts with /admin
        pool admin_pool
    }
}

'when' is mandatory; 'if' is optional for conditional logic.

Switch statements efficiently handle multiple conditions:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    switch -glob [string tolower [HTTP::host]] {
        "www.example.com" { pool www_pool }
        "api.example.com" { pool api_pool }
        "*.example.com" { pool wildcard_pool }
        default { HTTP::respond 404 content "Unknown host" }
    }
}

Options: -glob (wildcards), -regexp (regex), -exact (default). Always include 'default' case.

Route traffic based on TLS SNI without decrypting:

when CLIENT_ACCEPTED {
    TCP::collect
}

when CLIENT_DATA {
    # Parse SNI from ClientHello
    set sni [SSL::extensions -clienthello sni]
    switch $sni {
        "app1.example.com" { virtual vs_app1 }
        "app2.example.com" { virtual vs_app2 }
        default { reject }
    }
    TCP::release
}

Alternatively, use Local Traffic Policies with SNI conditions for simpler implementations.

Configure high-speed logging (HSL) for production iRule logging:

1) Create log destination:
tmsh create sys log-config destination remote-high-speed-log hsl_dest pool-name logging_pool

2) Create log publisher:
tmsh create sys log-config publisher hsl_pub destinations add { hsl_dest }

3) Use in iRule:
when RULE_INIT {
    set static::hsl [HSL::open -publisher /Common/hsl_pub]
}

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    HSL::send $static::hsl "Request from [IP::client_addr]\n"
}

HSL provides high-performance logging to remote servers.

WebSocket support requires proper configuration:

1) Use HTTP profile with websocket support:
tmsh modify ltm profile http my_http oneconnect-transformations disabled

2) For SSL, ensure upgrade headers pass through:
when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { [HTTP::header "Upgrade"] eq "websocket" } {
        # Disable OneConnect for this connection
        ONECONNECT::detach disable
    }
}

3) Consider idle timeouts - WebSockets need longer timeouts:
tmsh modify ltm profile tcp my_tcp idle-timeout 3600

The 'after' command schedules code execution after a delay:

when CLIENT_ACCEPTED {
    # Execute after 5000ms (5 seconds)
    after 5000 {
        log local0. "Connection still active after 5s"
    }
}

Use cases: delayed actions, timeouts, scheduled cleanup. Note: 'after' callbacks execute in separate context. There is no 'before' command; use events and timing logic instead.

Implement blue-green deployments using pool switching:

1) Create two pools (blue and green):
tmsh create ltm pool pool_blue members add { ... }
tmsh create ltm pool pool_green members add { ... }

2) Use iRule for traffic routing:
when HTTP_REQUEST {
    # Check data group for active version
    if { [class lookup "active_version" "deployment_config"] eq "green" } {
        pool pool_green
    } else {
        pool pool_blue
    }
}

3) Switch by updating data group. Or use priority groups for gradual migration.

Use geolocation for location-based routing:

1) Ensure geolocation database is loaded
2) Use iRule with GeoIP commands:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    set country [whereis [IP::client_addr] country]
    switch $country {
        "US" { pool pool_us }
        "EU" -
        "GB" -
        "DE" -
        "FR" { pool pool_eu }
        default { pool pool_default }
    }
}

For advanced GSLB, use BIG-IP DNS (GTM) with topology load balancing.

Insert X-Forwarded-For without iRules using HTTP profile:

tmsh modify ltm profile http my_http insert-xforwarded-for enabled

This automatically adds the client IP to the X-Forwarded-For header. For more complex scenarios (existing header handling, multiple proxies), use iRules:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    HTTP::header insert "X-Forwarded-For" [IP::client_addr]
}

Encrypt cookies for security:

1) Use built-in cookie persistence encryption:
tmsh modify ltm persistence cookie my_cookie encrypt-cookies enabled

2) For custom encryption via iRule:
when HTTP_RESPONSE {
    set encrypted [AES::encrypt $aes_key [HTTP::cookie "session"]]
    HTTP::cookie "session" $encrypted
}

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { [HTTP::cookie exists "session"] } {
        set decrypted [AES::decrypt $aes_key [HTTP::cookie "session"]]
    }
}

Initialize AES key in RULE_INIT.

HOST::lookup performs DNS resolution within iRules:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    # Resolve hostname to IP
    set ip [HOST::lookup [HTTP::host]]
    log local0. "Host [HTTP::host] resolves to $ip"

    # Route based on resolved IP
    if { $ip starts_with "10." } {
        pool internal_pool
    }
}

Note: DNS lookups add latency. Cache results using tables for frequently queried hostnames. Consider data groups for static mappings.

Implement cookie persistence for sticky sessions:

1) Using built-in cookie persistence:
tmsh create ltm persistence cookie my_cookie defaults-from cookie cookie-name "BIGIPSERVER" expiration 0
tmsh modify ltm virtual my_vs persist replace-all-with { my_cookie }

2) Or with custom iRule:
when HTTP_RESPONSE {
    HTTP::cookie insert name "SERVERID" value [IP::server_addr] path "/"
}

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { [HTTP::cookie exists "SERVERID"] } {
        pool my_pool member [HTTP::cookie "SERVERID"] 80
    }
}

Implement canary deployments using weighted routing:

1) Create pools for stable and canary versions:
tmsh create ltm pool pool_stable members add { ... }
tmsh create ltm pool pool_canary members add { ... }

2) Use iRule with percentage routing:
when HTTP_REQUEST {
    # 10% to canary
    if { rand(100) < 10 } {
        pool pool_canary
    } else {
        pool pool_stable
    }
}

3) Adjust percentage as confidence grows. Or use ratio load balancing between pools.

CLIENT_DATA triggers when client data is available after TCP::collect:

when CLIENT_ACCEPTED {
    TCP::collect
}

when CLIENT_DATA {
    # Inspect raw TCP payload
    set data [TCP::payload]

    # Make routing decision
    if { [string match "*SSH*" $data] } {
        virtual ssh_virtual
    } else {
        TCP::release
        pool default_pool
    }
}

Use for protocol detection, SNI routing, or custom protocol handling.

The persist command sets persistence records for session affinity:

# Source address persistence
when CLIENT_ACCEPTED {
    persist source_addr [IP::client_addr]
}

# Universal persistence with custom key
when HTTP_REQUEST {
    set session_id [HTTP::header "X-Session-ID"]
    persist uie $session_id
}

# Cookie persistence
when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { [HTTP::cookie exists "session"] } {
        persist uie [HTTP::cookie "session"]
    }
}

Use with Universal persistence profile for custom keys.

iFiles store files on BIG-IP for use by iRules and configurations:

# Create iFile from local file
tmsh create sys file ifile my_html /var/tmp/maintenance.html

# Use in iRule
when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { [active_members my_pool] == 0 } {
        HTTP::respond 503 content [ifile get my_html]
    }
}

Use iFiles for: maintenance pages, JavaScript files, CSS, error pages. They're stored in configuration and sync between HA pairs.

Route traffic based on HTTP headers:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    # Route by custom header
    switch [HTTP::header "X-Environment"] {
        "staging" { pool staging_pool }
        "production" { pool production_pool }
        default { pool default_pool }
    }

    # Route by Accept header (content negotiation)
    if { [HTTP::header "Accept"] contains "application/json" } {
        pool api_pool
    }

    # Route by API version header
    if { [HTTP::header "API-Version"] eq "v2" } {
        pool v2_pool
    }
}

FLOW::statistics provides traffic statistics collection:

# Enable detailed statistics
when CLIENT_ACCEPTED {
    # Tag flow for statistics collection
    FLOW::statistics enable
    FLOW::statistics application "MyApp"
}

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    # Set additional dimensions
    FLOW::statistics collect dimension "uri" value [HTTP::uri]
}

Statistics appear in AVR (Application Visibility and Reporting) or can be exported to external analytics platforms.

URL rewriting modifies request URIs before forwarding to servers:

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    # Add prefix
    HTTP::uri "/app1[HTTP::uri]"

    # Remove prefix
    if { [HTTP::uri] starts_with "/legacy" } {
        HTTP::uri [string range [HTTP::uri] 7 end]
    }

    # Replace path
    set uri [HTTP::uri]
    set uri [string map {"/old/" "/new/"} $uri]
    HTTP::uri $uri
}

Create a SNAT pool for source address translation:

tmsh create ltm snatpool my_snat_pool members add { 10.0.0.50 10.0.0.51 10.0.0.52 }

Assign to virtual server:
tmsh modify ltm virtual my_vs source-address-translation { type snat pool my_snat_pool }

SNAT pools distribute outbound connections across multiple IPs, useful for high-volume scenarios or when servers limit connections per source IP.

Data groups store lists of values for efficient iRule lookups. Types: address (IPs), string (key-value), integer (ranges). Create via TMSH:

# Address data group
tmsh create ltm data-group internal blocked_ips type ip records add { 10.0.0.1 { } 10.0.0.2 { } }

# String data group
tmsh create ltm data-group internal redirects type string records add { "/old" { data "/new" } }

Access in iRules using class match and class lookup commands.

Use different variable scopes in iRules: 1) Local variables exist only in current event: set var "value", 2) Request-scope persist across events for same request: set ::var "value", 3) Static variables persist across all requests: set static::var "value" (set in RULE_INIT). Example:

when RULE_INIT {
    set static::debug 1
}

when HTTP_REQUEST {
    set ::client [IP::client_addr]
}

when HTTP_RESPONSE {
    if { $static::debug } { log local0. "Client: $::client" }
}

Response chunking (Transfer-Encoding: chunked) streams responses without Content-Length. This affects iRules because HTTP::collect requires knowing the size. Handle chunked responses:

when HTTP_RESPONSE {
    if { [HTTP::header exists "Content-Length"] } {
        HTTP::collect [HTTP::header "Content-Length"]
    } elseif { [HTTP::header value "Transfer-Encoding"] eq "chunked" } {
        # Use RESPONSE_DATA with chunked callback
        HTTP::collect 1000000 ;# max to collect
    }
}

Limit connections per IP using iRule with tables:

when CLIENT_ACCEPTED {
    set client [IP::client_addr]
    set count [table incr -subtable conn_limit $client]
    if { $count > 100 } {
        reject
    }
}

when CLIENT_CLOSED {
    table incr -subtable conn_limit [IP::client_addr] -1
}

Alternatively, use Rate Shaping or DoS protection profiles for more sophisticated limiting.

Traffic classes categorize traffic for QoS and statistics. Create a traffic class:

tmsh create ltm traffic-class my_class description "API Traffic"

Assign in iRule:
when HTTP_REQUEST {
    if { [HTTP::uri] starts_with "/api" } {
        CLASSIFY::class set my_class
    }
}

Traffic classes enable per-application statistics collection and can be used with rate shaping for bandwidth management.
